            <br />
            <p><strong>Kinetic energy</strong></p>
            <br />
            <p>
                To calculate an object's Kinetic energy, we need to look at the components of an object in motion.
            </p>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <figure style="margin-bottom:0em">
                            <img src="~/images/topics/energy/lesson3/giphy.gif" alt="Car on a road" class="responsive" />
                            <figcaption>Taken from https://giphy.com/gifs/82nxC17BUZwJ8XHXBa/html5 </figcaption>
                        </figure>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>
                <strong>Mass.</strong> All objects have
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="Often confused with weight, mass is how much matter something is made up of.">
                    mass
                </a>
                which is measured in
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="This is the standard unit for measuring mass. A kilogram is 1000 grams and often abbreviated
                   to kg.">
                    kilograms
                </a>
                (kg). From your experience of driving a car, you may know that the more weight you put in the car, the
                harder you have to get the engine to work to get the car to move. The lighter the car is, the less work
                the engine has to do. This means more energy is needed to move a car with a higher mass.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Speed.</strong> An object that is moving has a
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:#2FA4E7; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="We normally use miles per hour, or a unit of distance per a unit of time. In physics, we use
                   metres per second. Any reference to miles per hour will also be provided in metres per second for
                   the equations, but you can simply Google a conversion calculator.">
                    speed
                </a>
                at which it is travelling. If you wanted to walk faster, you would need to use more energy and running
                would use even more energy than walking. To move slower would require less energy and standing still
                would use a negligible amount of energy.
            </p>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">Kinetic Energy</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E<sub>k</sub> = ½mv<sup>2</sup></h1>
                        <p class="card-text"><u><b>Where;</b></u></p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>E<sub>k</b> is the Kinetic Energy store measured in joules</p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>½</b> is a half of 1, normally put in a calculator as 0.5</p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>m</b> is the mass of an object measured in kilograms (kg)</p>
                        <p class="card-text">
                            <b>v<sup>2</sup></b> is the speed of the object in metres per second,
                            but it has been
                            <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #2FA4E7;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                               title="To square a number is to multiply it by itself.">
                                squared
                            </a>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
